<tr>
	<td class="alt1" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>Abividad</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Initiate<br />
		
	
	<br />
	Joined: Jun 2002<br />
	Location: So. Cal.
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt1" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>I have worked my skill up to the point where I am trivial at shrink potions. I and am also still looking for the next economically viable potion to continue increasing my skill with, and would love to see more such potions introduced into the game, but here are several thoughts about potions in general from my limited experience, since this is my first, and main character in EQ<br />
<br />
First, with regard to cost of potions. I agree with Mitrian and others above. The cost to produce many potions at the high end of our skill level prices them right out of viability for the benefit of their effect, even though all our potions except ITA do stack with any spell giving the same benefit<br />
<br />
Smiths can make any armor sold by NPC vendors I think. Fletchers can make any product a NPC vendor sells. Why can Shaman not make any potion that a NPC sells?<br />
<br />
It seems VI has tiered spells into three levels, (1-22, 23-44, 44+) with regard to focus effects. I think that could be a natural breakdown for players getting additional benefits from potions we might make other than the Kilva's line.<br />
<br />
As much of an economic boon as snare, root, dd, dot, ect potions would be to us, they unfortunately are not logical effects that a person would gain from drinking a potion. Seems to me that the effect should be directed upon the person drinking the potion, and giving them the ability to cast it upon something else ruins the internal logic of alchemy <br />
<br />
I wish you all well<br />
<br />
Abividad &lt;Sentinels of Light&gt;<br />
Shaman of the forty-first circle<br />
Povar</p>
	
	
	
